words directed to us, with our eyes fixed on our Lord's eyes as we sit at His feet}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \cf1\insrsid286953 . As we look into those eyes, how do we feel? Are we 
comforted, encouraged, ashamed? Are we aware of our incompleteness, our brokenness, as we are taught about things that we barely do? What is our Lord saying to us, as his eyes shine with wisdom and love, and yet also with such perfection and brightness th
at we feel the sharp sting of self condemnation and shiver in the cold of our own darkness? 
\par 
\par He tells us of a stone, and we know He is speaking }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \i\cf1\insrsid286953\charrsid7550650 of Himself}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \cf1\insrsid286953 .}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \cf1\insrsid286953 
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \cf1\insrsid286953 The corner stone is a heavy and perfectly formed stone, and upon it the whole edifice rises. It is t
he foundation of all other stones, and for the edifice to be strong, all these stones must also be perfectly formed, and fitted to the corner stone. We know that we are to be these stones, as He has told us "God is able of these stones to raise up childre
n unto Abraham." }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \fs16\cf1\insrsid286953\charrsid7550650 (Mat 3:9)}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \cf1\insrsid286953 . }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \cf1\insrsid286953 
